{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"feaac3bb-dfef-4c7f-a852-d8e073c943a8","content":"## What Happened\n\nC# 14 / .NET 10 expanded **implicit span conversions**: `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is now preferred by overload resolution. So the compiler resolves:\n\n```\narray.Contains(num)\n```\n\nto **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)`** instead of the old **`Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`**.\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it cannot be captured in expression trees. The tree may get built referencing the span-based overload, but `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)` fails at runtime because the expression interpreter cannot handle ref struct types.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload:\n\n**Option A — static call:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option B — cast away the array type:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nEither approach forces resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`, which expression trees fully support.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f4fcf4e-1200-4812-ac1d-43c2403727b1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"extension everything\"), but more relevantly, there's been a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in .NET 10, `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains` resolution changed, or there's a new extension member that takes priority.\n\n\nThe real culprit is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` became applicable to arrays in .NET 10 since arrays implicitly convert to `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and the compiler now prefers this more specific overload over `Enumerable.Contains` for array types. This is a known breaking change that started around .NET 9.\n\nThe issue is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` uses `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, which is a ref struct that expression trees can't support. The workaround is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` instead, which forces the compiler to use the LINQ version that works with expression trees.\n\nBut wait—the user mentioned this throws at runtime, not compile time. If the expression tree compiled successfully, that suggests they might be using the interpreter mode with `preferInterpretation: true`, which could behave differently than compiled delegates.\n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe the issue is that in C# 14 or .NET 10, the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, which takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. Expression trees normally can't contain ref struct types, so this should fail at compile time with an error like CS8640. But if the user is seeing a runtime error instead, perhaps they're building the expression tree dynamically, or there's a scenario where the compiler allows it through but the interpreter chokes on it at runtime. being preferred for arrays. This was documented as a breaking change. The compiler would give a compile-time error when used in expression trees because `ReadOnlySpan<T>` can't be used in expression trees.\n\nBut in .NET 10 / C# 14, maybe the situation is different. Let me think...\n\nActually, I think the scenario might be:\n1. The code was compiled targeting .NET 9 where `Enumerable.Contains` was resolved\n2. After upgrading to .NET 10 SDK (C# 14 compiler), the overload resolution changed to prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains`\n3. This causes a compile-time error, not a runtime error\n\nBut the user says \"throws at runtime\"... \n\nLet me reconsider. Maybe the expression tree is constructed manually via `Expression.Call` etc., not via a lambda expression. In that case, the tree might reference a method that doesn't exist or behaves differently on .NET 10. Or perhaps the code compiles because the expression tree somehow gets through, but at runtime when the interpreter tries to execute it, it can't handle the `Span`-based method.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is the breaking change in .NET 9 where `Enumerable.Contains` and similar methods on arrays now resolve to `MemoryExtensions` overloads that use `Span<T>`, which can't be used in expression trees. I'm realizing the implicit span conversions introduced in C# 13 changed method overload resolution, making `MemoryExtensions.Contains` a better match than `Enumerable.Contains` for array arguments. Since the user says it worked on .NET 9, this breaking change likely happened in C# 14 with .NET 10, possibly as a refinement to how extension methods are resolved when span conversions are involved. is when the overload resolution actually starts preferring `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains`.\n\nActually, I think the breaking change was documented for .NET 9 but the \"params span\" overloads and implicit span conversions didn't fully kick in for overload resolution until the language/runtime matured. \n\nOK, I think I should just give the best answer I can:\n\n**What happened**: In C# 14 / .NET 10, the compiler resolves `array.Contains(item)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, it cannot be represented in expression trees. This either causes a compile-time error or, if the expression tree is constructed dynamically at runtime, a runtime error.\n\nThe user's code shows a lambda expression tree that throws at runtime, which suggests the expression tree is being built dynamically rather than as a compile-time constant. When the runtime tries to construct the expression tree with the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` method call, it fails because ref structs can't be used in expression trees. Fail at compile time with an error about ref structs in expression trees. So the user should get a compile-time error, but they're saying it's a runtime issue. Unless the expression tree compiles fine because the compiler falls back to `Enumerable.Contains` in that context, but then `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)` behaves differently in .NET 10.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that C# 13 introduced first-class span support with implicit conversions from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so the compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` when calling `.Contains()` on an array. Since expression trees can't represent `ReadOnlySpan<T>` as a ref struct, this breaks at runtime. The fix would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` instead. I'm considering whether this is actually a compile-time error that the user is describing loosely as a runtime error, since that's common when people aren't being precise about the distinction. The most likely explanation is that .NET 10 changed method overload resolution to prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` for arrays due to implicit span conversions, and I should give a clear answer about what caused the issue and how to fix it. should note that in .NET 9 this was already flagged as a breaking change: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/compatibility/core-libraries/9.0/linq-extensions\n\nThe title was \"New LINQ extension methods ambiguity\" and it affected `Order`, `Contains` and others. But in .NET 9, this was about the new overloads being ambiguous in some cases. Perhaps in .NET 10 they fully broke expression trees with this.\n\nOK, I'll give my best answer. The key insight is that the C# compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` for arrays due to implicit span conversions making it a better match. The problem is that `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct and can't be used in expression trees, so this breaks any code trying to use `.Contains()` in a LINQ expression. To fix it, you can either call `Enumerable.Contains()` explicitly as a static method or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` first.","outputTokens":3640,"requestId":"D006:83F89:12A97F:1662D4:69E819E8"},"id":"11b9a1c1-8383-4fd9-bcbe-a7c05ce02edf","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:45:34.409Z","parentId":"726ec8c2-bc2e-4c8d-b9aa-25570558d190"}
